explanation:
Explain why each symbol is required to assess the MISRA rule (memcmp shall not be used to compare null terminated strings):

- strcmp
  - The target uses strcmp(stream->stream_name, old). Confirming the actual implementation or macro mapping for strcmp is required to ensure it is not implemented as or substituted with memcmp (which would trigger the MISRA rule).

- memcmp
  - The MISRA rule explicitly concerns memcmp. The symbol (and any uses of it) must be inspected in the target and its callees to determine whether memcmp is used to compare null-terminated strings related to this code path (e.g., comparing stream_name, old, or new).

- strncpy
  - The function calls strncpy to copy new into stream->stream_name and explicitly sets the last byte to 0. Inspecting strncpy usage and semantics helps confirm that stream_name is intended and guaranteed to be a null-terminated string (relevant when determining if any memcmp uses would be comparing null-terminated strings).

- OS_stream_internal_record_t
  - This struct defines stream->stream_name (type and length) and socket_domain. You must inspect the field type/size and semantics to know whether stream_name is a null-terminated string and thus whether any memcmp usage against it would violate MISRA.

- OS_stream_table
  - The global table from which stream pointers are obtained. Needed to understand how stream records are stored/typed and whether access via OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET yields valid stream objects for which string comparisons apply.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET
  - Macro/function used to retrieve the stream pointer from the table index/token. Its definition may affect types or casts (could conceivably hide alternative comparisons) and is needed to confirm stream->stream_name is the same string object considered by strcmp.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken
  - Used (indirectly via OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET or other macros) to map iterator tokens to array indices. Inspecting it confirms the indexing/access are correct and that the record referenced is indeed the stream record whose name is compared.

- OS_ObjectIdIterateActive
  - Initializes the iterator; inspecting it helps confirm which objects are iterated and whether the loop can yield entries whose stream_name should be considered null-terminated strings (scope of the comparison).

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext
  - Controls the iteration and token values used to access OS_stream_table. Needed to ensure the token leads to valid stream entries (so any string comparisons are against valid null-terminated buffers).

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy
  - Cleans up iterator state; included to allow full inspection of the iterator lifecycle (ensures no side-effects alter string state or comparisons during iteration).

- OS_TranslatePath
  - Called at function entry for old/new. It manipulates the input strings and writes into local buffers (old_path/new_path). It may itself contain string comparisons using memcmp on null-terminated strings; must be inspected to find any memcmp-based string comparisons related to the same inputs.

- OS_FileRename_Impl
  - The actual rename implementation may perform path/string comparisons internally (and could use memcmp incorrectly). It must be checked to ensure no memcmp-on-NT-string violations occur in the rename path relevant to this function.

- OS_MAX_LOCAL_PATH_LEN
  - Defines the size of old_path/new_path buffers and may affect whether strings are null-terminated after translation/truncation. Knowing buffer sizes is necessary to reason whether comparisons in this flow are operating on null-terminated strings.

- OS_SocketDomain_INVALID
  - The code checks stream->socket_domain against this constant to decide whether to compare stream_name. Understanding its definition ensures the condition limits the comparison to the intended record types (i.e., only file streams), relevant when determining the scope of any memcmp misuse.

Summary: these symbols let the analyzer determine (1) whether any memcmp calls exist in the target or its callees acting on null-terminated strings (direct violation), (2) whether strcmp used here is an acceptable string comparison (not a memcmp alias), and (3) whether the operands involved (stream->stream_name, old, new, old_path/new_path) are null-terminated strings so that any memcmp use would fall under the MISRA prohibition.
